ch of this Anglo-Norman family has been in Ireland since the 12th century. Its name has been Gaelicized as <b>Tirial</b>.","English: habitational name from Tirril (Cumbria), which derives from Old Norse <i>tyri</i> ‘resinous wood’ + <i>erg</i> ‘shieling’."]}]},{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"POIX","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Swiss French: unexplained. In Switzerland it is found mainly in the Valais Canton.","Catalan: nickname from <i>moix</i> with various possible meanings, including ‘cat’, ‘drunk’, and ‘lame’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde TYREL DE POIX was born in 1220, in Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France, her father, Gauthier V Tirel de Poix, was 39 and her mother, Ade Heloise De Liomer, was 33. She had at least 3 daughters with Guillaume De Cayeux Sur Mer. She died in 1270, in Cayeux-sur-Mer, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1220–1270":"1220–1270","1225–1290":"1225–1290","1243–1293":"1243–1293","1244–1304":"1244–1304","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1182–1229":"1182–1229","1187–1249":"1187–1249","1220":"1220","1187":"1187","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1304":"1304","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","1229":"1229","Cayeux-sur-Mer, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Cayeux-sur-Mer, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Poitiers, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1220–1270":"1220–1270","1225–1290":"1225–1290","1243–1293":"1243–1293","1244–1304":"1244–1304","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1182–1229":"1182–1229","1187–1249":"1187–1249","1220":"1220","1187":"1187","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1304":"1304","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","1229":"1229","Cayeux-sur-Mer, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Cayeux-sur-Mer, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Ranska","Poitiers, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Ranska"},"fr":{"1220–1270":"1220–1270","1225–1290":"1225–1290","1243–1293":"1243–1293","1244–1304":"1244–1304","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1182–1229":"1182–122